						               													<description>&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#162;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#171;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#185;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#187;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#142;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#191;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#162;&amp;#227;&amp;#128;&amp;#128;&amp;#239;&amp;#189;&amp;#158;&amp;#229;&amp;#144;&amp;#155;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#175;&amp;#233;&amp;#173;&amp;#148;&amp;#230;&amp;#179;&amp;#149;&amp;#233;&amp;#153;&amp;#163;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#175;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#168;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#164;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#191;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#188;&amp;#239;&amp;#189;&amp;#158; (Ars Notalia -You are a magic circle creator-) is a drawing game from Japan. Players are students of magic, having taken up a 4 week internship at a magical research company. Their goal is to improve their grades and hopefully gain full-time magic work.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each week they complete a magical research on a particular. A spell is formed from a combination of two word cards (English included). Players use agreed symbols to represent the components of the spell (water, fire and so on). Each player draws a version of the spell from the symbols required.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;At the end of the course, each player studies the spells drawn by the other students, and casts a secret vote on how well they have been drawn. Players are looking for how easily the drawing is to read, and how well it matches the requirements of the spell.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Once all the votes are cast, the scores are revealed and totalled up. The best score wins the game and a new job.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players must try to draw out on paper a spell, decoratively and cleverly. But it must be recognisable as the spell, and not too difficult to read and interpret correctly. A spell that is too easy, or too obscure, should score lower marks than a more finely crafted work.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game has been presented as a Print'n'Play, with the black &amp;amp; white files online under a password, being released for the low price of &amp;yen; 500.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
